{"title_page": "Shu of Wey\u2013Kang", "text_new": "[[File:British Museum Kang Hou Gui Top.jpg|250px|thumb|Bronze Vessel of Shu Feng, British Museum. 12th Century BCE-11 Century BCE]]\n'''Shu of Wey\u2013Kang''' or '''Kang-shu of Wey''' ({{zh|\u885b\u5eb7\u53d4}}), '''Shu Feng of Kang''' ({{zh|\u5eb7\u53d4\u5c01}}), also known as given name '''Feng''' (\u5c01), [[Temple name]] '''Liezu''' (\u70c8\u7956)<ref>Guoyu, Volume 15, Jinyu 9</ref> was a [[Zhou dynasty]] feudal lord and the founder of the state of [[Wey (state)|Wey]]. He was the ninth son of [[Ji Chang]].<ref>{{Cite book|title=\u53f2\u8a18\u7814\u7a76\u96c6\u6210: \u53f2\u8bb0\u4eba\u7269\u4e0e\u4e8b\u4ef6|last=Zhang|first=Dake|publisher=Hua Wen Press|year=2005|isbn=9787507515657|location=|pages=}}</ref> Feng was also the full-brother of [[King Wu of Zhou]], [[Duke of Zhou]], [[Shu Zhenduo of Cao]] and [[Gao, Duke of Bi|Gao the Duke of Bi]].<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite book|title=Records of the Grand Historian|last=|first=|publisher=Zhonghua Book Company|year=1982|isbn=9787101003048|location=|pages=Vol.37}}</ref>\n\nShu Feng was at first the lord of Kang (\u5eb7). After [[Rebellion of the Three Guards]], Shu Feng received the capital city of Shang dynasty [[Zhaoge]] as his fief.<ref name=\":0\" /> This event marked the beginning of Wey's history. \n\nShu Feng had a son named Mao. Mao succeeded his title and was later known as {{ill|Count Kang of Wey|zh|\u536b\u5eb7\u4f2f}}.<ref name=\":0\" /> \n\nIn 1931 CE, Shu Feng's bronze vessel [[Kang Hou Gui]] was unearthed. The vessel's inscription shows that Shu Feng was sent to Zhaoge with the purpose of pacifying the people of Shang after their defeated rebellion.<ref>Inscriptions of Kang Hou Gui</ref>\n\nBefore sending Shu Kang to Zhaoge, Duke of Zhou worried that the young brother of his might not be capable of handling a new environment. It is said that Duke of Zhou made three admonitions for Shu Feng to prevent him from any wrong-doing.\n\nShu Feng's state of Wey would outlive all other Chinese states during Zhou dynasty except [[Qin dynasty|Qin]] which unified China. Wey existed even after Qin's unification of the six major states.\n\nShu Feng's shrine was located in [[Qi County, Hebi|Qi county]]\uff0cHenan province.<ref>{{Cite book|title=\u8fd1\u4ee3\u7a17\u6d77|last=Rong|first=Mengyuan|publisher=People's press of Sichuan|year=|isbn=9787220002052|location=|pages=14}}</ref> It is currently abandoned. \n\n== References ==\n<references />\n\n{{Monarchs of Wey (state)}}\n[[Category:Zhou dynasty nobility]]\n[[Category:Monarchs of Wey]]\n", "text_old": "[[File:British Museum Kang Hou Gui Top.jpg|250px|thumb|Bronze Vessel of Shu Feng, British Museum. 12th Century BCE-11 Century BCE]]\n'''Shu Feng of Kang''' ({{zh|\u5eb7\u53d4\u5c01}}), also known as '''Shu of Wey\u2013Kang''' or '''Kang Shu of Wey''' (\u885b\u5eb7\u53d4), given name '''Feng''' (\u5c01), [[Temple name]] '''Liezu''' (\u70c8\u7956)<ref>Guoyu, Volume 15, Jinyu 9</ref> was a [[Zhou dynasty]] feudal lord and the founder of the state of [[Wey (state)|Wey]]. He was the ninth son of [[Ji Chang]].<ref>{{Cite book|title=\u53f2\u8a18\u7814\u7a76\u96c6\u6210: \u53f2\u8bb0\u4eba\u7269\u4e0e\u4e8b\u4ef6|last=Zhang|first=Dake|publisher=Hua Wen Press|year=2005|isbn=9787507515657|location=|pages=}}</ref> Feng was also the full-brother of [[King Wu of Zhou]], [[Duke of Zhou]], [[Shu Zhenduo of Cao]] and [[Gao, Duke of Bi|Gao the Duke of Bi]].<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite book|title=Records of the Grand Historian|last=|first=|publisher=Zhonghua Book Company|year=1982|isbn=9787101003048|location=|pages=Vol.37}}</ref>\n\nShu Feng was at first the lord of Kang (\u5eb7). After [[Rebellion of the Three Guards]], Shu Feng received the capital city of Shang dynasty [[Zhaoge]] as his fief.<ref name=\":0\" /> This event marked the beginning of Wey's history. \n\nShu Feng had a son named Mao. Mao succeeded his title and was later known as {{ill|Count Kang of Wey|zh|\u536b\u5eb7\u4f2f}}.<ref name=\":0\" /> \n\nIn 1931 CE, Shu Feng's bronze vessel [[Kang Hou Gui]] was unearthed. The vessel's inscription shows that Shu Feng was sent to Zhaoge with the purpose of pacifying the people of Shang after their defeated rebellion.<ref>Inscriptions of Kang Hou Gui</ref>\n\nBefore sending Shu Kang to Zhaoge, Duke of Zhou worried that the young brother of his might not be capable of handling a new environment. It is said that Duke of Zhou made three admonitions for Shu Feng to prevent him from any wrong-doing.\n\nShu Feng's state of Wey would outlive all other Chinese states during Zhou dynasty except [[Qin dynasty|Qin]] which unified China. Wey existed even after Qin's unification of the six major states.\n\nShu Feng's shrine was located in [[Qi County, Hebi|Qi county]]\uff0cHenan province.<ref>{{Cite book|title=\u8fd1\u4ee3\u7a17\u6d77|last=Rong|first=Mengyuan|publisher=People's press of Sichuan|year=|isbn=9787220002052|location=|pages=14}}</ref> It is currently abandoned. \n\n== References ==\n<references />\n\n{{Monarchs of Wey (state)}}\n[[Category:Zhou dynasty nobility]]\n[[Category:Monarchs of Wey]]\n", "name_user": "Th\u1eafng L.\u0110.Q.", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Shu_of_Wey%E2%80%93Kang"}
